  "prompt": "Is it a misconduct in cricket for a batsman to walk out the ground when the umpire decides a dismissal to be not out but actually it isn't?",
  "response": "In cricket, if a batsman walks off the field after being given not out by the umpire, this action is generally considered poor sportsmanship or a breach of the spirit of the game, rather than formal misconduct. The Laws of Cricket do not explicitly penalize a batsman for walking off in these circumstances; however, it can create controversy and may be frowned upon by players, officials, and spectators alike.\n\nThe expectation in cricket is that players respect the decisions made by umpires, and a batsman walking off after being adjudged not out could be viewed as undermining that respect. If a batsman believes they are out, the conventional wisdom is that they should continue playing until the umpire decides otherwise. \n\nIn summary, while it may not be classified as \"misconduct\" under the formal laws, it is not regarded as a commendable or sportingly acceptable practice.",
